reviews.text: Iconic breakfast and brunch in North Williamsburg with an incredible burger, first ever I had with an egg on it and never turned back.
One of my fav place in Brooklyn

Such a great spot! The ricotta pancakes were amazingly fluffy and just sweet enough. The crispy chicken sandwich and fries totally hit the spot. Staff was nice even though it was packed, and the outdoor seatingâ€™s perfect for a sunny day.

I skipped this place for years after two visits, but the third was worth it. Employees show wonderful warmth and recommended truly delicious food. I enjoyed what I ate and who brought it. The service here stands out above everything else! The feeling here is complete satisfaction.
Been coming here since 2008 and it hasnâ€™t changed a bit. Itâ€™s just perfect

five leaves was the first restaurant i visited on my first ever trip to nyc in 2017.
ever since then coming back here has become a tradition.
8 years on and the spot is still just as warm and welcoming, albeit way more busy which is incredible to see because the place deserves to thrive. easily my fav spot in the city (i fully blame the ricotta pancakes).
i havenâ€™t been to nyc in years but coming back here today felt like coming home in so many ways.
thank you cody for taking such great care of me and thank you everyone at five leaves for even making a tourist feel like a part of the community. ğŸ«¶ (also pls restock those tote bags, the nation needs them!!)

This place sets standards others should follow. This spot speaks to those who appreciate good meals. The restaurant deserves its good reviews. Skilled staff who gave perfect suggestions and entertained my family throughout dinner. Five Leaves has secured our family's return visits.

Breakfast at Five Leaves in Williamsburg was fantastic! Fluffy ricotta pancakes, fresh granola, and great coffee. Cozy, relaxed vibe with lots of natural light. Friendly, laid-back service. Perfect spot for a leisurely breakfast or weekend brunch.

Five Leaves never disappoints! The Moroccan Scramble was bursting with flavorâ€”perfectly spiced, hearty, and balanced in every bite. Pairing that with their Ricotta Pancakes was absolute magic. The pancakes were light, fluffy, and indulgent, with just the right touch of sweetnessâ€”truly next level.

The vibe is classic Five Leaves: lively, stylish, and welcoming, with a menu that always manages to impress. If youâ€™re in the area, this spot is a must for both comfort and creativity

Just sat for 8 minutes without a waiter so much as look at me. Place is half empty and a couple of waiters having chats with buddies. If they canâ€™t get the basics of service right they def canâ€™t get the food right. Nice location-menu did not really entice. Didnâ€™t stick around to try the food.
The best FRENCH DIP. Ever but you have to get in before 3.

arrived right in the golden sunshine hour yesterday during happy hour. popped my head in and was greeted immediately by a kind woman who plopped me at a table in the sun..oh how i love the sun!

i hovered over the happy hour menu, torn between fish and chips or falafel, when camilla???my server (if memory serves she was wearing a blue striped dress and was very kind!) came with perfect guidance. falafel it was a decision i didnt regret soooo delicious the portion was just enough to tide me over before a late dinner.

not too pricey either, so def recommend for happy hour energy and a cute little space for a solo moment. i sat, watched the world drift by, and had to scamper off when a message buzzed through, but what a tiny, lovely slice of time at this place thanks for all!

Food was decent but service here sucks. I wouldnâ€™t return. There are so many other better restaurants in the neighborhood. The outside seating is very uncomfortable and the waiters donâ€™t greet you.
Best pancakes in Brooklyn hands down. The burger is good too. I will always come back.

The chef understands what makes people truly enjoy eating. I genuinely liked this spot. Service at this restaurant is memorable. Really yummy and the plates are loaded. My regular choice. We're excited about coming back again.

Their brunch was decent. Overall pretty tasty although the fries too salty.

Service was ok. Could be more attentive.

The vibe was off. Very cramped and chaotic. Not a relaxing brunch. But we were seated inside. Maybe the outdoor seating is better.

In conclusion: meh

Lieu visitÃ© plusieurs fois, le genre dâ€™adresse quâ€™on voudrait garder que pour soit ! Jâ€™adore ++++ je recommande le blt mais aussi le bacon, les hash browns, ou les pancakes : accrochez vous ils sont fat !

You know a place is memorable when a single dish stays with youâ€”and the Five Leaves burger does exactly that. Itâ€™s a bold creation: grass-fed beef, a fried pineapple ring, houseâ€‘pickled beets, harissa mayo, and a sunny-side-up egg all stacked on a ciabatta bun. The combinationâ€”sweet, savory, rich, and unexpectedâ€”works in delicious harmony.

More than just the food, Five Leaves carries a distinct personality. The interior blends vintage nautical charm with urban intimacyâ€”think cozy corners, worn textures, and a relaxed, hipsterâ€‘friendly vibe.

Fries was so good and the watermelon in the watermelon salad was very ripe.

Burgers were gigantic and hard to eat.

Service was super super slow though.

Lots of out door seating all in the shade.
Delicious and great vibe!

Donâ€™t fall for the hype especially if you actually care about flavor.
I came here on my birthday craving sweet pancakes and left seriously disappointed. I know pancakes usually have a simple flavor and thatâ€™s fine. But for $22 you would expect something more. A hint of citrus a touch of something fresh anything to make it feel worth it. But no. Just fluff with zero taste. The strawberries had this weird garlic-like flavor the bananas were brown overall a total letdown.

Even the table next to me sent theirs back. I donâ€™t know why but it seemed like they also noticed something off.

Donâ€™t trust places hyped by people who grew up eating bland food and now call anything trendy amazing. If you have a real palate especially if you are Brazilian this place will likely disappoint you.
Solid Brooklyn restaurant, great walkable area and awesome food & drinks.

Long wait time for food to come. Food came out cold and isnâ€™t all that great. Tad overpriced for the quality and drink sizes.

Came here for brunch with my friend and our dogs - the food was good but unfortunately we had a bad experience. We sat outside (of course because we had dogs with us), but it was a very hot day and there was no shade at our table. We asked multiple times if we could move to a table with shade, but kept being told those tables were saved for bigger parties. We were almost done with our meal and no one had been seated in the section we asked to move to. Eventually, we just asked for the check and packed up our food. I'd understand if there weren't that many tables available or if people were waiting to be seated, but that was not the case at all.

Great food with friendly service
Amazing service, and the place has a good vibe. The only small "complaint" is that the plate I ordered was a bit smaller than I thought.  The oysters were very fresh and delicious.

Brunch Vibes Worth the Hype!

Had brunch with my cousin and let me just say, every bit of the hype is so well deserved. We went on a weekday around 11am, so it wasnâ€™t too busy, which made it even more enjoyable. From the moment we walked in, we were greeted with a warm welcome by the friendly staff. That energy sets the tone right away!

Iâ€™d read about the Ricotta Pancakes and had to see what the fuss was about, they did not disappoint. We also had the Grain Bowl with a side of steak and halloumi, and every bite was packed with flavor and texture.

I donâ€™t drink alcohol, but I love
a good mocktail. â€œWaters of Lifeâ€ was a winnerâ€”especially if youâ€™re into bold ginger and turmeric flavors like I am.

Best part? You can treat yourself without breaking the bank. Trust me, this spot is a gem. Iâ€™ll definitely be back soon!

Was excited to come here cause Iâ€™d heard good things. Shame the wait staff were rude and pass aggressive (and if you think Iâ€™m being sensitive so many reviews of this place echo the same sentiment.) Felt super uncomfortable while eating here - shame cause the food was good.

Very bad experience over all.  Server and host were rude and seamed inconvenienced by having to retrieve an extra plate of lemons for the painfully mediocre mussels. Canâ€™t but help but think as the only Black and visibly trans patron in this establishment that the real inconvenience was having to serve me. The difference in how I was treated compared to white patrons was palpable. The host seemed annoyed when I asked for a table and the server literally changed his tone from bright and welcoming to flat whenever he had to address me. The restaurant was half empty so the lack of service cannot be blamed on staff feeling overwhelmed. I left a 40% tip in hopes that the tipping pool takes care of the people of color working in back of house. If youâ€™re Black or a person of color steer clear.

Layout/atmosphere
*Bar area; tables; tables on sidewalk; outdoor dining structure in street

Food/drink
*Sage Scrambled Egg Sandwich (aged cheddar, mayo, spiced tomato jam) - very good; fluffy eggs; cheese & mayo mixed well together; soft bun; wasnâ€™t a fan of the tomato jam; sandwich itself on the smaller side
*Avocado (side order) - solid; salted
*Housemade hot sauce - Good
Great happy hour! Outdoor seating, dog friendly and great margaritas!
It was raining and we sat outside and our server still checked in on us despite the pouring rain. Food was excellent and portion sizes are big. Would recommend and come back.
Great people watching and delicious food and drinks !
Oysters were perfect and great drinks!

At the corner of Bedford and Lorimer, across from McCarren Park, Five Leaves hums with the ritual of weekend brunch. Its weathered faÃ§ade and amber-lit interior suggest a bistro pasticheâ€”half Brooklyn, half borrowed memory. The peeling bathroom walls, the worn wood bar, the stickered entryway: all curated to a rustic perfection that feels accidental by design.

We ordered the Egg Sandwich, the Big Breakky with steak, and a latte. The food delivered: the egg sandwich was soft, well-sauced, and satisfying; the steak, properly charred and flavorful; the chorizo, boldly salty; and the scrambled eggs, golden and elegant. The mushrooms were earthy, though less memorable. The latte, however, was forgettableâ€”an afterthought in a city of coffee ambition.

Still, to judge Five Leaves on food alone would miss the point. This is a brunch of scenes and rolesâ€”young families, hungover couples, stylists taking meetings, dogs under tables. The vibe, not the menu, is what draws the line that wraps around the corner.

We ordered the egg sandwich, the big breakky plate, and a latte. The food tastes goodâ€”nothing mind-blowing, but definitely something Iâ€™d come back for. The egg sandwich has a rich, cheesy flavor, and the tomato sauce adds a great extra layer. I especially liked the sautÃ©ed mushrooms on the big breakfastâ€”they have a unique herbal/spiced taste that stands out. The latte was just okay. Service overall was a bit slow, likely due to how busy it was, so be prepared for a bit of a wait.

The line was pretty long. But the line was worth the wait because food was amazing. The Big Breakkyâ€™s eggs was salty, and soft at the same time. The grilled chorizo was chewy, soft, and seasoned well. The toast was softer than a pillow. And the sÃ¡uteed mushrooms was juicy(I added a lot of black pepper and salt to make it taste better(my mom did not like it)). The Sage egg sandwichâ€™s scrambled eggs was pretty much the same as the big breakkyâ€™s but the grilled tomato was spicy and sweet.
I always come back for the ricotta pancakes bc they are very good!!
Cute spot. Nothing special. Food was decent. Service could use improvement.
Iâ€™ve only been for brunch. You canâ€™t go wrong with the pancakes or Moroccan scramble!

Iâ€™ve had dinner here twice in the past week, and Iâ€™ll start with the good news... the food is genuinely great. Unfortunately, the service doesn't match the quality coming out of the kitchen.

Hereâ€™s what happened both times: if you order an appetizer, your main dish gets delayed because the chef is timing it as a "coursed meal", even if you order something small like truffle fries. No one explains that up front. So while youâ€™re waiting, youâ€™ll notice other tables who arrived after you getting served before you. Itâ€™s confusing and honestly frustrating when you're hungry and just trying to enjoy your evening.

The staff didnâ€™t seem particularly attentive either. Not unfriendly, just not very present or aware of how long we were waiting. A little communication would have made a big difference.

I really wanted to love the full experience here, which was probably the reason for my return. However, the food alone almost made me overlook the service issues. But after two visits with the same pattern, itâ€™s hard to ignore.

If you go, just know youâ€™re in for great food but the overall dining experience might leave something to be desired.
